{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "AtmosphericPressureProfile",
        "description": "Atmospheric pressure, density, and vertical pressure gradient as a function of altitude for an isothermal atmosphere. Couples the hydrostatic equation with the ideal gas law: the scale height H = R*T/(M_air*g) (Eq. 1.4) sets the e-folding altitude, the barometric formula p = p_0*exp(-z/H) (Eq. 1.5) gives pressure, the ideal gas law rho = M_air*p/(R*T) (Eq. 1.2) gives density, and the hydrostatic equation dpdz = -rho*g (Eqs. 1.1/1.3) gives the pressure gradient. Migrated from AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc391 src/seinfeld_pandis_ch1.jl:151 (`AtmosphericPressureProfile` @component). Implements Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Chapter 1 Equations 1.1-1.5 for an isothermal atmosphere — the integrated, constant-scale-height form; a non-isothermal atmosphere would require numerical integration of Eq. 1.3. Parameterized as observed-only: altitude z and temperature T are inputs (parameters in standalone form, with R, M_air, g, p_0 as further parameter inputs carrying their upstream @constant values), and H, p, rho, dpdz are the four algebraic outputs. The upstream `5.3 AtmosphericPressureProfile Compilation` test compiles the component with `inputs = [app_nns.T]`, confirming T is an input.",
        "tags": [
            "atmospheric_dynamics",
            "seinfeld-pandis",
            "observed-only",
            "ch1",
            "pressure-profile"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "AtmosphericDynamics.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-xn9x)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed. Wiley. Chapter 1, Section 1.2 (Atmospheric pressure and density), Eqs. 1.1-1.5 (hydrostatic equation, ideal gas law for density, scale height, and the barometric formula for an isothermal atmosphere). ISBN 978-0-471-72018-8."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "AtmosphericPressureProfile": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: AtmosphericDynamics.jl@816cc391:src/seinfeld_pandis_ch1.jl:151\nUpstream `AtmosphericPressureProfile` is an MTK `@component` with R, M_air, g, p_0 as `@constants`, z as a `@parameter`, and T(t), H(t), p(t), rho(t), dpdz(t) as `@variables`. It carries four algebraic equations (Seinfeld & Pandis Ch 1): H = R*T/(M_air*g) (Eq. 1.4), p = p_0*exp(-z/H) (Eq. 1.5), rho = M_air*p/(R*T) (Eq. 1.2), and dpdz = -rho*g (Eqs. 1.1/1.3). T appears only on equation right-hand sides — it is an input, not a computed output — so the four equations close exactly over the four states H, p, rho, dpdz. For standalone serialization (and to make the component well-posed in isolation) T, z, R, M_air, g, and p_0 are declared as parameters here, leaving H, p, rho, dpdz as the algebraic states. This matches the bead's `(S, observed-only)` classification in docs/migration-tracker.md and the IdealGasLaw / ScaleHeight / BarometricFormula serialization pattern in this directory. The upstream `5.3 AtmosphericPressureProfile Compilation` test (test/seinfeld_pandis_ch1_test.jl:471) confirms this input/output split: it compiles the component with `inputs = [app_nns.T]`, leaving H, p, rho, dpdz as the computed unknowns. Constant values (R = 8.314 J/(mol*K), M_air = 0.02897 kg/mol, g = 9.807 m/s^2, p_0 = 101325.0 Pa) come from the upstream module's R_GAS / M_AIR / G_ACCEL / P_0 (Seinfeld & Pandis Appendix A). The four algebraic equations are unchanged from upstream.\n\nUpstream provides only structural (`1.3 AtmosphericPressureProfile Structure`) and compilation (`5.3 AtmosphericPressureProfile Compilation`) tests for this component — no numerical-accuracy test. The inline `tests` here therefore anchor on physical reference values: standard sea-level conditions (p = p_0, rho ~ 1.226 kg/m^3, dpdz ~ -12.0 Pa/m at T = 288 K), the e-folding property at z = H (p = p_0/e), and the scale heights cross-checked against scale_height.esm (8427.87 m at 288 K, 7403.65 m at 253 K, 9305.77 m at 318 K).\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-6): observed-only algebraic system (no ODE integration); 1e-6 covers float64 roundoff in the multiply/divide and exp(-z/H) expression chain across the altitude range (0-20 km) and the atmospheric temperature range (253-318 K)."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-6
            },
            "variables": {
                "z": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Altitude above sea level (sea-level datum z = 0)"
                },
                "T": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "K",
                    "default": 288.0,
                    "description": "Temperature of the isothermal atmospheric column — an input, assumed constant with altitude (sea-level standard 288 K)"
                },
                "R": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J/(mol*K)",
                    "default": 8.314,
                    "description": "Universal gas constant"
                },
                "M_air": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/mol",
                    "default": 0.02897,
                    "description": "Molecular weight of dry air (28.97 g/mol)"
                },
                "g": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s^2",
                    "default": 9.807,
                    "description": "Gravitational acceleration"
                },
                "p_0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "default": 101325.0,
                    "description": "Standard sea-level pressure (Seinfeld & Pandis Appendix A)"
                },
                "H": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "description": "Atmospheric scale height H = R*T/(M_air*g) — the altitude over which pressure falls by a factor e (Eq. 1.4)"
                },
                "p": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "description": "Atmospheric pressure at altitude z (barometric formula, Eq. 1.5)"
                },
                "rho": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "description": "Air density at altitude z (ideal gas law, Eq. 1.2)"
                },
                "dpdz": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "Pa/m",
                    "description": "Vertical pressure gradient dp/dz = -rho*g (hydrostatic equation, Eqs. 1.1/1.3)"
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "_comment": "Eq. 1.4 - Atmospheric scale height: H = R*T/(M_air*g)",
                    "lhs": "H",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": ["R", "T"]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": ["M_air", "g"]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Eq. 1.5 - Barometric formula (isothermal atmosphere): p = p_0*exp(-z/H)",
                    "lhs": "p",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "p_0",
                            {
                                "op": "exp",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "-",
                                        "args": [
                                            {
                                                "op": "/",
                                                "args": ["z", "H"]
                                            }
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Eq. 1.2 - Ideal gas law for air density: rho = M_air*p/(R*T)",
                    "lhs": "rho",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": ["M_air", "p"]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": ["R", "T"]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "_comment": "Eqs. 1.1/1.3 - Hydrostatic equation: dpdz = -rho*g",
                    "lhs": "dpdz",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": ["rho", "g"]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "sea_level_standard",
                    "description": "Standard sea-level reference (z = 0, T = 288 K). The barometric formula reduces to p = p_0 at the datum; the ideal gas law then gives the standard sea-level air density (~1.226 kg/m^3) and the hydrostatic gradient dpdz = -rho*g (~-12.0 Pa/m). This is the boundary condition the whole profile is anchored to. The system is algebraic, so p is also asserted at t = 1.0 to confirm time-invariance.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 0.0,
                        "T": 288.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "H", "time": 0.0, "expected": 8427.870183108378 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 101325.0 },
                        { "variable": "rho", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.2259213249739396 },
                        { "variable": "dpdz", "time": 0.0, "expected": -12.022610434019425 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 1.0, "expected": 101325.0 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "one_scale_height",
                    "description": "At an altitude equal to the scale height (z = H(288 K) = 8427.87 m) the pressure falls by exactly a factor e: p = p_0/e ~ 37275 Pa. This is the defining property of the scale height (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 1.5); the expected p matches barometric.esm's one_scale_height case. Density and the pressure gradient fall by the same factor e.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 8427.870183108378,
                        "T": 288.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "H", "time": 0.0, "expected": 8427.870183108378 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 37275.38437669639 },
                        { "variable": "rho", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.450991251951567 },
                        { "variable": "dpdz", "time": 0.0, "expected": -4.422871207889018 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "troposphere_10km",
                    "description": "Upper-troposphere case at 10 km altitude (T = 288 K). With the isothermal scale height H ~ 8428 m the estimate is p ~ 309 mbar; the real atmosphere is ~265 mbar near this altitude (Seinfeld & Pandis Table 1.4), the expected overshoot of the constant-H idealization. Exercises pressure and density well above the surface.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 10000.0,
                        "T": 288.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 30932.07823850794 },
                        { "variable": "rho", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.3742442076323634 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "stratosphere_20km",
                    "description": "Deep-decay case at 20 km altitude (z ~ 2.37 H, T = 288 K): pressure has fallen to ~9.4 kPa and the hydrostatic gradient to ~-1.1 Pa/m. Exercises the small-pressure tail of the exponential.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 20000.0,
                        "T": 288.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 9442.817312145833 },
                        { "variable": "dpdz", "time": 0.0, "expected": -1.1204274753865657 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "cold_atmosphere_5km",
                    "description": "Cold mid-troposphere column (T = 253 K) at z = 5 km. The lower temperature shrinks the scale height to H ~ 7404 m (cross-checked against scale_height.esm cold_253K), so pressure decays faster with altitude than the 288 K case.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 5000.0,
                        "T": 253.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "H", "time": 0.0, "expected": 7403.649848355624 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 51572.60347926007 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "warm_atmosphere_5km",
                    "description": "Warm column (T = 318 K, ~45 C) at z = 5 km. The higher temperature stretches the scale height to H ~ 9306 m (cross-checked against scale_height.esm warm_318K), so pressure decays more slowly with altitude than the 288 K case. With cold_atmosphere_5km this brackets the temperature dependence at fixed altitude.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 5000.0,
                        "T": 318.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "H", "time": 0.0, "expected": 9305.773327182167 },
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 59206.55805835972 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "nonstandard_p0",
                    "description": "Non-default sea-level pressure (p_0 = 100000 Pa) at z = 5 km, T = 288 K. Verifies p scales linearly with p_0 while the exponential decay factor stays fixed; density rho = M_air*p/(R*T) follows p proportionally.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "z": 5000.0,
                        "T": 288.0,
                        "p_0": 100000.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "p", "time": 0.0, "expected": 55251.776171869395 },
                        { "variable": "rho", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.6684858687567893 }
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "profile_vs_altitude",
                    "description": "Pressure and density as a function of altitude for an isothermal atmosphere at the sea-level standard temperature (T = 288 K, H ~ 8428 m). Reproduces the canonical exponential decay of Seinfeld & Pandis Eqs. 1.5 and 1.2 from the surface to 30 km.",
                    "initial_state": {
                        "type": "per_variable",
                        "values": {}
                    },
                    "parameters": {
                        "T": 288.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "z",
                                "range": { "start": 0.0, "stop": 30000.0, "count": 31, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "p_vs_z",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Atmospheric pressure p as a function of altitude z at T = 288 K (Eq. 1.5).",
                            "x": { "variable": "z", "label": "Altitude (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "p", "label": "Pressure (Pa)" }
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "rho_vs_z",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "Air density rho as a function of altitude z at T = 288 K (Eq. 1.2).",
                            "x": { "variable": "z", "label": "Altitude (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "rho", "label": "Air density (kg/m^3)" }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "pressure_over_altitude_and_temperature",
                    "description": "Two-dimensional sweep over altitude z (surface to 20 km) and the isothermal column temperature T (250-310 K). Surfaces the joint dependence of pressure on altitude and on temperature: warmer columns have a larger scale height and so decay more slowly with altitude.",
                    "initial_state": {
                        "type": "per_variable",
                        "values": {}
                    },
                    "parameters": {},
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "z",
                                "range": { "start": 0.0, "stop": 20000.0, "count": 21, "scale": "linear" }
                            },
                            {
                                "parameter": "T",
                                "range": { "start": 250.0, "stop": 310.0, "count": 13, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "p_heatmap",
                            "type": "heatmap",
                            "description": "Atmospheric pressure p as a function of altitude z and isothermal column temperature T.",
                            "x": { "variable": "z", "label": "Altitude (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "T", "label": "Temperature (K)" },
                            "value": { "variable": "p", "reduce": "final" }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
